## Structure

In this ecosystem, every `page.tsx` file located within `app/(pages)/` is strictly a declarative shell. It is the gatekeeper of routing and SEO, not the place for implementation logic. Its responsibilities are limited to importing `Metadata`, defining `generateMetadata` through the dedicated `@rccyx/seo` package, and configuring static or dynamic generation parameters. Most importantly, it must perform any necessary server-side pre-fetching via the server-side caller before returning a single, high-level page component from the implementation directory. A `page.tsx` file should never contain inline JSX beyond the root component and its necessary providers; it is a server component by default to ensure maximum SEO efficiency and initial load performance.

The component directory is the heart of the frontend architecture, governed by a recursive and strictly scoped hierarchy. Every route has a corresponding folder in `src/app/components/pages/[route]/`, where the entry point is always `index.tsx`. Components that are exclusive to a specific page must reside in a `components/` sub-folder within that page's directory. If a component is shared by multiple elements within that specific page scope but isn't quite a sub-component, it lives in a local  `/shared` directory.

This logic scales upward: components shared across the entire application live in the root-level `shared` directory, while components intended for use across multiple apps in the monorepo must be promoted to the `@rccyx/components` package. There is an unforgivable rule of one component per file. If you find yourself writing a second component, you create a new file. Period. This ensures that every piece of the UI is modular, testable, and easy for a refactor without side effects.

To maintain sanity in a monorepo, we utilize a rigorous import aliasing system that eliminates the need for brittle relative paths. The `@` symbol is reserved exclusively for monorepo-level internal packages such as `@rccyx/design`, `@rccyx/api`, and `@rccyx/seo`, or for specifically approved third-party packages. Local application files are addressed using the `~` alias, starting from the `src` root. You are strictly forbidden from using `../` to escape a component's scope; if a component or utility is needed outside its current directory, it must be moved to the appropriate shared level in the hierarchy. Furthermore, all TypeScript imports must use the `import type` syntax for interfaces and types to keep the generated JavaScript clean and avoid circular dependency hell.

The way we write functions is designed for clarity and future-proofing. Any function that accepts more than a single input must receive its arguments as a single, destructured object. This removes the ambiguity of positional arguments and makes the code self-documenting. For example, a function creating a post must take an object containing the title, slug, and content rather than a string-heavy list of arguments. Within these functions, we prefer `interface` for defining the shape of simple objects and `type` for more complex logic like unions, intersections, or utility types.

Exports are the public API of your modules, and we do not use default exports unless NextJS or the framework requires it. Every component, hook, or utility must be a named export. This prevents naming collisions and makes the "Find All References" tool actually useful. Filenames for React components must use PascalCase to match their exported names, while hooks use camelCase. Folder names are strictly kebab-case to ensure cross-platform file system compatibility. When building UI, always check the `@rccyx/design/ui` package before creating a custom element; we rely on a standardized set of Radix-based components.

Global UI state is managed via MobX, utilizing the `observer` pattern from `mobx-react-lite` and a centralized `useStore` hook that has access to all stores within a single app. Do not pollute components with complex local state if it belongs in a store. For animations, we use `framer-motion` (via `@rccyx/design/motion`). All visibility toggles and layout transitions should be wrapped in `AnimatePresence` and utilize the `motion` prefix. For forms, the standard is `React Hook Form` combined with `Zod` for schema validation, ensuring that data is validated on the client and server using the exact same type  definitions from the RPC layer.

Example Folder Mapping:

```text
apps/my-cool-blog/src/app/
├── (pages)/
│   └── [post]/
│       └── page.tsx           <-- Thin shell, SEO, Server Fetching
└── components/
    └── pages/
        └── [post]/
            ├── index.tsx      <-- Named export, Root Implementation
            ├── components/
            │   └── PostData.tsx <-- Local sub-component
            ├── hooks/
            │   └── useTracker.ts <-- Local hook
            └── shared/
                └── SharedIcon.tsx <-- Local shared asset
```

You are to act as a senior architect. When asked to create a new feature, you must first determine the correct scope (local page, app-level misc, or package-level). You will never export more than one component per file and will never use default exports. If you are generating a new route, start with the declarative `page.tsx` and move the heavy lifting to `components/pages/`.



### Third-Party Rules

- ❌ **Do NOT** install any third-party package (e.g. `framer-motion`, `lucide`, etc.) unless approved first.
